	<img class="rightFloat" src="../Media/SS_LN_005.jpg" mode="1" id="1001"  /><media class="leftFloat" src="../Media/SS_LN2b.mp3" mode="4" id="1002"  /><p align="left"><font color="#000000">The prospect of living longer has brought about a change in people's (6) <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q1" type="droptarget" /></font>. The elderly no longer conform to Shakespearean stereotypes of old age, the middle-aged feel younger than previous generations while young people today regard themselves as (7) <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q2" type="droptarget" /></font> at sixteen.</font></p><p align="left"><font color="#000000">People who retire after 2010 are unlikely to be as (8) <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q3" type="droptarget" /></font> as previous generations of pensioners. There are two reasons for this. Firstly, attitudes and beliefs formed when we are young tend to remain with us throughout life, in much the same way that (9) <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q4" type="droptarget" /></font> loyalties do. Secondly, the next generation of pensioners will have had a better (10) <font color="#0000ff"><input id="q5" type="droptarget" /></font>.</font></p>
